5\n- **Category**: Documentation\n- **Confidence**: 90\n- **Problem**: Doc claims \"above the posting is its transaction, then the @code{item} base which both share, then the report, and finally the session.\" But `post_t::lookup` (src/post.cc:701, 838) falls through directly to `item_t::lookup`, never to `xact_t::lookup`. Posting-scope evaluations therefore see post → item → report → session (via `bind_scope_t`); the parent transaction is *not* in the chain. (The transaction's own fields like `code` and `payee` are duplicated in `post_t::lookup` precisely because xact isn't traversed.)\n- **Impact**: Misleads anyone who tries to reason about which scope answers a name.\n- **Fix**: Replace \"above the posting is its transaction, then the @code{item} base which both share\" with \"above the posting is the @code{item} base it shares with the transaction\".\n\n---\n\n### [HIGH] Double-quoted strings are not always strings\n- **File**: doc/ledger3.texi#L9523-L9526 (Literals section)\n- **Category**: Documentation\n- **Confidence**: 95\n- **Problem**: The doc says `'hello'` and `\"hello\"` \"Both produce @code{STRING} values; if you want an amount value, write the amount without quotes.\" But `src/token.cc:271-315` shows that double-quoted text is **first** parsed as an amount (`amount_t::parse` with `PARSE_NO_ANNOT`); only on amount-parse failure does it fall back to a string. So `\"$10.00\"` in an expression yields an `AMOUNT`, not a string, while `'$10.00'` yields a string. Single and double quotes are not interchangeable.\n- **Impact**: Examples like `commodity == \"USD\"` may behave differently from `commodity == 'USD'` when the right-hand side parses as an amount.\n- **Fix**: Document that single quotes always produce a string, while double quotes try amount-parse first and fall back to a string. The advice \"Use the literal that does not collide with any contained quotes\" should be replaced with guidance to prefer single quotes for strings.\n\n---\n\n### [MEDIUM]